We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive direct the:

(39) Municipal Accountant to prepare Journal Entry Voucher to adjust the properties below the capitalization threshold and ensure that all future acquisitions of properties below the capitalization threshold of ₱50,000.00 be recorded in accordance with COA Circular No. 2022-004;

(40)Property Custodian/Inventory Committee to:
 Formulate plans and strategize the complete conduct of physical count of all its PPE, and prepared and submit the RPCPPE not later than January 31 of the ensuing year in compliance with Section 124 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Volume I;

(41) Attach the required property stickers for PPE with the required number format under COA Circular No. 2020-06 in order to have a uniform property identification system.

(42)We further recommended and management agreed that the Municipal Accountant and the Property Custodian prepare and maintain the PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards, respectively, in order to facilitate the periodic reconciliation if the PPE accounts with results of the physical inventory taking.

We recommended and management agreed that the LCE require the Municipal Accountant to:

(43) Prepare the Schedule of the Accounts Payable, with proper aging;

(44) Make the necessary adjustments to arrive at the correct balances of the affected accounts in the financial statements;

(45) Verify the validity of the ₱4,972,847.44 balance of Accounts Payable and ₱36,259.40 balance of Due to Officers and Employees from CY 2021; and

(46) Revert the accounts payable without valid claims.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive:

(64) submit the required certification that the activities/services of the job order personnel cannot be provided by regular or permanent personnel of the agency (for first claim); 

(65) direct the human resource personnel to prepare and submit to the audit team the individual contracts for each JO personnel which contain the specific job description and the specific office to where he/she is assigned and rates on a daily basis;

(66) direct the signing of approval of DTRs to JOs’ immediate supervisors;

(67) submit the lacking DTRs and Accomplishment Reports for the payments amounting to ₱4,878,949.00; and

(68) stop granting cash advances to the Municipal Treasurer for the JO services when complete documents are not attached to the disbursement voucher.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to:

a) Direct the Municipal Accountant to 

(89) prepare and submit the BRS of all its depository bank accounts monthly, take up reconciling items, and prepare necessary adjusting journal entries; 

(90) regularly reconcile the book balances and bank records vis-à-vis the cashbook and prepare adjusting entries, if any; 

(91) regularly submit the mandatory reports and the supporting documents within the reglementary period; and 

(92) draw a JEV to adjust the understatement of the Cash in bank-LCCA account by of ₱1,513,481.76;

(93) Direct the Municipal Treasurer to 
(a) post the balances of the Cash in Bank- LCCA in the cashbook, with proper segregation of the sources of funds;

We recommended and the LCE agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant to:

(100) Enforce the immediate liquidation and/or refund of the unliquidated cash advances and refrain from granting additional cash advance to officials and employees with outstanding balances until the previous cash advances are fully settled /liquidated;

(101) Designate staff to closely monitor the liquidation of outstanding cash advances;

(102)    Reconcile the unliquidated or outstanding cash advances made by the Municipal Treasurer;

(103) Perform the duties/responsibilities of the Accountant specified under Item 7.0 of COA Circular No. 2016-005 and determine the unliquidated cash advances that are non-moving for more than ten years where settlement/collectability could no longer be ascertained and initiate the request for write-off as allowed in the same Circular;

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:
MDRRMO to ensure proper monitoring on the utilization of LDRRMF and immediately communicate PPAs that are in need of funding;
Municipal Budget Officer to:
be cautious in preparing the appropriations in the Annual Budget, as well as the Supplemental Budgets;
ensure all disbursement are in accordance with the approved Annual Budget together with the LDRRMFIP and strictly monitor the availability of appropriation before the approval of an obligation;
prepare and maintain separate RAAOs for QRF, MOOE, and CO, in relation to the approved LDRRMFIP;
Municipal Accountant to:
effect the necessary entries for the transfers of unspent balance and adjust the balance of Trust Liabilities-DRRM account at year-end; and
provide appropriate disclosure on the LDRRMF balance to the Notes to Financial Statements
Municipal Treasurer to:
cause the complete transfer of the adjusted unexpended balances for the previous years and likewise the 2024 LDRRMF to and from the Special Trust Fund account; and
be careful in issuing checks to avoid illegal utilization of funds.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive to:
Direct the Municipal Accountant, to submit the necessary documents to support   payment for the procured Vehicle:
Original copy of Dealers/Suppliers' Invoices showing the quantity, description of the articles, unit and total value duly signed by the dealer or his representative, and indicating receipt by the proper agency official of items delivered;
The bid documents from the posting in PhilGeps to the Awarding of Contract;
Warranty Security for a minimum period of one year, after acceptance by the procuring entity of the delivered vehicle;
Supplier’s Business and Tax Registration; and
Photo documentation of purchased unit
Submit proof of compliance of Authority to Purchase Motor Vehicle from the DILG.
This recommendation is without prejudice to the issuance of Notices of Suspension/Disallowance, if warranted.

